Assuming here that the categorized list is directly provided, the median value of a sorted list / array can be directly found by checking the middle element(s).

Since the given list is already sorted and contains odd number (15) of integers, the median value will be the value right in the middle of the array.

Elements in an array are addressed starting from position 0 (1st), position 1 (2nd), and so on, and up to position N-1 (last) for an array of N elements. nth item of an array can be referenced as array[n] in C++. For a list of 15 elements like our case, the middle element's index will be (15 - 1) / 2 = 7th position (8th element as array started from 0). 

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int arr[15] = {1, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 31, 37, 43, 47, 53, 59};
    int median;
    int arrSize = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);

    median = arr[(arrSize - 1) / 2];

    cout << "Median value is: " << median;

    return 0;
}
```

When you run this C++ program, it will output:

```Median value is: 23```

Which is the value in the middle of the sorted array.

